Data Visualization & Insights
Price History Graphs: Don’t just show the current and lowest price; show the journey. An interactive line chart (using libraries like Chart.js or Recharts) helps users see if a price drop is a common occurrence or a rare flash sale.

"Buy or Wait" AI Recommendation: Based on historical data, you could add a simple logic (or a small ML model) that tells the user: "Price is likely to drop further in 2 weeks" or "Lowest in 6 months—Buy Now!"

2. Smart Notifications
Threshold Alerts: Let users set a specific "Target Price." Instead of just tracking, the system sends an email or browser push notification only when the item hits that specific number.

Stock Alerts: Prices often drop right before an item goes out of stock. Adding an "In Stock/Out of Stock" indicator is a huge value-add.

3. Comparison & Community
Cross-Platform Comparison: If I track an iPhone 16 on Flipkart, your tool could automatically find and display the price for the same model on Amazon (and vice-versa) on the same card.

Public Price Drops Feed: A "Trending" section showing what other users are tracking that recently hit an all-time low.

4. Advanced Organization
Collections/Folders: As the "7 products tracked" grows to 50, let users group them (e.g., "Home Office Setup," "Baby Products," "PC Build").

Browser Extension: A companion Chrome extension that lets users click a "Track" button directly while browsing Amazon or Flipkart, instead of copying and pasting URLs.

5. Monetization & UX (The "Pro" Touch)
Affiliate Integration: Automatically append your affiliate tags to the "Buy Now" buttons to monetize the traffic.

Dark Mode: Since it's a dashboard-heavy app, a dark mode toggle is always a crowd favorite for developer-centric projects.